HandsOnMORE

Maider Aguerralde Martin & Ãngeles Arzalluz

2025-01-20

MORE (Multi-Omics REgulation) is an R package which is able to infer condition-specific multi-omic regulatory networks. It is developed by the BiostatOmics Lab and is publicly available on BiostatOmics GitHub.

MORE applies Multiple Linear Regression (MLR) or Partial Least Squares (PLS) to model a target omic expression as a function of experimental variables, such as disease or treatment, and the target featureâ€™s potential regulators. It uses advanced variable selection techniques ElasticNet or Iterative Sparse Group Lasso for MLRs or Jack-Knife or Permutation techniques in combination with the VIP for PLS models to infer the significant regulators of the target omic expression for the biological system under study. Additionally, MORE is capable of incorporating prior regulatory knowledge and clinical data.

Installation

Currently, the package can be installed directly from GitHub using the devtools R package by:

install.packages("devtools")
devtools::install_github("BiostatOmics/MORE")

For an extended version of MORE functionalities, visit MOREsâ€™ UserGuide available here.

For further information on the methodological aspects, visit the preprint of the paper.

Load MORE

library(MORE)

Data

In this tutorial we will use the STATegra dataset whose reduced version is available in MORE package. Even a more reduced version of this data is also included in MORE to run the UsersGuide example.

The STATegra dataset contains time-series data for pre-B-cell differentiation in mice, including 6 time points (0h, 2h, 6h, 12h, 18h, 24h). A set of samples has been subject to drug-controlled induction of the Ikaros transcription factor, while the Control cells have not and, therefore, will not differentiate into B-cells.

We first load the data by:

load('STATegraReduced.RData')

DataSTATegra loads the following objects:

  • GeneExpressionDE: RNA-seq data. Matrix with differentially expressed genes across conditions in rows and samples in columns.

  • data.omics: List including each of the regulatory omics of the RNA-seq. Each omic is included in the list as a matrix with regulators in rows and samples in features.

  • associations: List containing pairs of genes and regulators known to interact, based on the literature and/or databases.

  • edesign: Matrix including the experimental design associated with each sample.

MORE requires that the GeneExpression matrix and all matrices of regulatory omics contain data from the same samples and in the same order. If sample labels differ, MORE will assume that samples are in the same order.

Below, we show a preview of each object so that the user knows how to format MOREsâ€™ input data.

MORE

To run MORE for any of its possible models, we use the function more(). The user can specify which type of regression model to apply (one of MLR, PLS1 or PLS2) with the parameter method, while with the parameter varSel, it can be specified which variable selection techniques to apply (EN or ISGL for MLR or Jack or Perm for PLS1 or PLS2). However, some parameters are common for any regression or variable selection technique type used:

  • omicType: vector with as many elements as the number of omics, indicating whether each contains numeric (0) or binary (1) values. If not provided, MORE will automatically detect the omic types. However, the user MUST stop the process if the automatic detection is wrong.

  • minVariation: vector of minimum change that a regulator must show across conditions to be included in the model.

  • scaleType: indicates the type of scaling factor that should be used (one of auto, softBlock or hardBlock).

  • interactions: By default, it is set to TRUE to allow MORE to test condition-dependent regulatory interactions. This effectively increases the number of predictors in the model but provides more interpretable information.

  • parallel: By default, is set to FALSE. Considers parallelization in numberOfCores-1 when set to TRUE or the number of cores the user asks when a number is provided.

Note: MLR and PLS1 models create a model for each of the target omic features provided. PLS2 creates a unique model for all the target omic features but cannot consider prior regulatory knowledge.

In this example, data was already somehow preprocessed, so we set a low cutoff for those regulatory omics that were not/barely filtered and left it at 0 for those already filtered.

## omic order: "miRNA"  "DNase"  "Methyl" "TF"
minVar = c(0, 0.1, 0.1, 0)
names(minVar) = names(data.omics)

MORE takes a unique covariate as the condition of the samples. In this data, we have information about the time and the type of the treatment. In this case, we will create MORE models to compare Ikaros vs control.

edesign = edesign[,-1, drop=FALSE]

MLR + EN

MLRmodel = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE,
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                associations = associations,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'EN',
                alfaEN = NULL,
                correlation = 0.7,
                method = 'MLR',
                parallel = TRUE)

Results

MLRmodel is a list containing the following objects:

names(MLRmodel)
## [1] "ResultsPerTargetF" "GlobalSummary"     "arguments"

ResultsPerTargetF

The list ResultsPerTargetF contains one object for each of the analyzed target features (genes in this example). We show the information MORE returns for the gene ENSMUSG00000000078:

  • Y: data.frame containing the response variable values for the gene (i.e.Â the gene expression values), the Y values fitted by the model, and the residuals.

  • X: data.frame containing the predictor variables included in the model.

  • coefficients: a matrix with the estimated coefficients for the regulators pointed as relevant. The sign and absolute value of the coefficients indicate the direction and the strength of the association between the gene and the regulator, respectively.

  • allRegulators: data.frame with all the potential regulators in rows and the following information in the columns: gene, regulator, omic, area (the third, optional column in the associations table), filter (whether the regulator has been filtered out of the model, and the reason) and Rel (1 if the model has selected the regulator or 0 if not).

  • relevantRegulators: a character vector containing the IDs of the relevant regulators selected by the model. If a multicollinearity â€œrepresentativeâ€ (mc) is detected as relevant, all the correlated regulators are also retrieved.

Notice how some regulators have _mc1_ followed by a number and letters R, N and P appended to their IDs (e.g.Â mc1_1_P). The first number indicates the subgroup of highly connected regulators in the correlation network, e.g.Â there may be two clusters of similarly correlated regulators, each of which has included a representative in the model: mc1_1 and mc1_2. When _R, this means that this regulator was selected as the representative for its group. When _N and _P, it means that this regulator is negatively or positively correlated with its representative, respectively.

GlobalSummary

The list GlobalSummary contains the general results of the created models. We show the information MORE returns:

  • TargetFNOregu: matrix containing information about the genes with no initial regulators.

  • TargetFNOmodel: matrix containing information about the genes for which MLR models could not be fitted and the reason why (either an error during MLR fit or a lack of regulators remaining after elastic net variable selection).

  • GoodnessOfFit: matrix that collects the R-squared value, the Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE), the Normalized RMSE (NRMSE), and the number of relevant regulators selected by the model (related). This helps filter results, for instance, by selecting the regulatory models that best explain the gene variance across the conditions.

  • ReguPerTargetF: matrix containing, for each omic and gene, the number of initial regulators supplied (-Ini), the number of regulators included in the initial model (-Mod) after the series of filters applied by MORE, and the number of relevant regulators included in the final model (-Rel).

  • GlobalRegulators: vector of the most relevant regulators, i.e., those relevant for a larger part of the genes. It selects the 3rd quartile of the regulator list after ranking them by their number of regulations.

  • HubTargetF: vector of genes that accumulate more regulators, according to the MORE models. The 3rd quartile of the gene list, ranked by the number of regulators.

MLR + ISGL

MLRISGLmodel = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE[1:20,],
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                associations = associations,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'ISGL',
                groupingISGL = 'MF_0.7',
                method = 'MLR')

To run MORE with Iterative Sparse Group Lasso, we slightly change the main functionâ€™s parameters. In this case, we would use groupingISGL instead of alfaEN to change from the EN alfa mixing parameter to the type of approach to consider when creating the groups in the ISGL. In this example, we use the multicollinearity approach (MF) with a correlation threshold of 0.7 to make the groups. Other options:

  • MF_X: Takes the same approach as in the multicollinearity filter. Grouping the variables which correlate more than X.
  • PCA_X: Extracts as many PCA components to explain X percent of the variability of the data and assigns the variables to the component in which they had the highest loadings.

PLS1 + Jack + VIP

PLSJackmodel = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE[1:20,],
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                associations = associations,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'Jack',
                alfa = 0.05,
                method = 'PLS1')

To run MORE with Partial Least Squares, we slightly change the parameters of the main function. In this case, we would use alfa instead of alfaEN to change from EN alfa mixing parameter to alpha (I type error) threshold to consider a p-value significant.

In the case of PLS models, we would talk about significant regulators instead of relevant regulators as we were doing so in MLR models. So outputs like ResultsPerTargetF$relevantRegulators change to outputs like ResultsPerTargetF$significantRegulators.

PLS1 + Perm + VIP

PLS1model = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE[1:20,],
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                associations = associations,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'Perm',
                alfa = 0.05,
                method = 'PLS1')

PLS2

All the above-presented models compute a unique model for each gene considered. However, when there is no prior regulatory knowledge, it could be beneficial to run a PLS2, which creates a unique model for all the genes. To do so, we run:

PLS2mmodel = more(targetData = GeneExpressionDE[1:20,],
                regulatoryData = data.omics,
                condition = edesign,
                omicType = 0,
                scaleType = 'auto',
                interactions = TRUE,
                minVariation = minVar,
                varSel = 'Perm',
                alfa = 0.05,
                method = 'PLS2')

Interpretating MORE results

First, we run the RegulationPerCondition() function, which returns a summary of the significant regulations for each gene. We will load the pre-computed results for all genes afterwards to avoid excessive runtime:

regpcond = RegulationPerCondition(MLRmodel)
head(regpcond)
##              targetF regulator omic     area representative  Group_0  Group_1
## 1 ENSMUSG00000000028      Atf5   TF promoter                 0.30780  0.23550
## 2 ENSMUSG00000000028     Foxm1   TF promoter                 0.39160  0.33150
## 3 ENSMUSG00000000028      Klf2   TF promoter                 0.06762  0.06762
## 4 ENSMUSG00000000028    Zfp629   TF promoter                -0.36240 -0.46210
## 5 ENSMUSG00000000028    Zfp787   TF promoter                 0.00000 -0.10170
## 6 ENSMUSG00000000028      Arnt   TF promoter          Bach2 -0.07001 -0.16520

Looking at the results of regpcond, we first make clear that Group_0 and Group_1 correspond to the control and Ikaros conditions, respectively (as codified in edesign). The corresponding coefficients can be interpreted as follows:

  • If two experimental groups have the same coefficients, the regulator has the same effect on the gene in both conditions.

  • If the coefficient is 0 in one of the groups, the regulator has no effect on the gene under that condition.

  • Experimental conditions with different, non-zero coefficients indicate that the regulator affects the gene in these conditions, but the magnitude of the effect is not the same for the groups.

To further investigate the results of MORE, letâ€™s start with some summary plots of the models computed.

The summaryPlot function represents the % of genes with relevant regulations and the % of regulations found to be relevant in each omic, depending on whether the bytargetF parameter is set to TRUE or FALSE. We can also stratify the results filtering by \(R^2\), e.g.Â see the percentage of genes for which the model explains at least 90% of the variance:

summaryPlot(MLRmodel, regpcond, filterR2 = 0.9)

summaryPlot(MLRmodel, regpcond, byTargetF = FALSE, filterR2 = 0.9)

Notice that transcription factors account for the majority of regulatory relationships and that, when looking at the % of regulations, all omic layers have more relevant regulations in the Ikaros condition, indicative of the activation of the gene regulation machinery as a result of the action of this transcription factor.

After this prior study, if one is interested in focusing their efforts on analyzing the regulatory networks of a subset of genes that were better modeled by MORE, they can use filterR2 to do so.

To create small regulatory networks, we will apply the filter previously used in this example. We can extract the regulations of the genes

regpcond_filtered = FilterRegulationPerCondition(MLRmodel, regpcond, filterR2 = 0.9)

Using the results obtained by more(), MORE can produce several plots to inspect the results.

A plot per gene can be obtained if no regulator is supplied, and all significant regulators detected for the gene, together with the geneâ€™s expression pattern, will be shown in a grid. Since our gene has many relevant regulators, we will show the regulatory patterns of the Snapc4 TF, which is representative of the mc1_1 group of correlated regulators. In this group, the Elk3 TF and the mmu-miR-466d-5p miRNA are negatively and positively correlated regulators with Snapc4, respectively. In addition, a regulator-specific plot can be produced if no gene, and only a regulator, is selected. Letâ€™s do this for miRNA mmu-miR-146a-5p, a miRNA that regulates 1 gene according to the MORE results:

plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = NULL, regulator = "mmu-miR-146a-5p", 
         order = TRUE,size = 6)
## 1 target features are regulated by mmu-miR-146a-5p

## [1] "ENSMUSG00000032383"

If the relationship between gen and regulator is difficult to discern in those plots, we can simplify them and try to see them in a scatterplot. Re-using the previous example:

plotMORE(MLRmodel, targetF = "ENSMUSG00000000149", regulator = "Snapc4", simplify =  TRUE)

We can also create the regulatory networks inferred by the model by:

networkMORE(regpcond_filtered, cytoscape = FALSE)

These networks are complex to analyze in R, so MORE provides an extension to explore them better using Cytoscape. To do so, Cytoscape MUST be open and operative when running:

networkMORE(regpcond_filtered, cytoscape = TRUE)

To look only at the different regulations, we can create differential regulatory networks by:

networkMORE(regpcond_filtered, group1 = '0', group2 = '1', cytoscape = FALSE)

Downstream analysis

MORE package also includes several other functionalities to do a complete downstream analysis.

Over Representation Analysis (ORA)

If the user has an annotation matrix, they can run an ORA either for the hub target features or the target features regulated by the global regulators, indicating TRUE or FALSE, respectively, on the byHubsparameter.

regincond_ikaros = RegulationInCondition(regpcond_filtered, cond = '1')

ORA_ikaros = oraMORE(MLRmodel,regincond_ikaros, byHubs = TRUE, annotation = annotation)

ORA_ikaros_globtarget = oraMORE(MLRmodel,regincond_ikaros, byHubs = FALSE, annotation = annotation)

Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA)

They can also run a GSEA to compare the results of two experimental conditions.

regincond_control = RegulationInCondition(regpcond_filtered, cond = '0')

gsea_out = gseaMORE(MLRmodel, regincond_control,regincond_ikaros,  annotation = annotation)

If the user is interested in analysing the regulatory networks associated with a pathway (e.g.Â a pathway that is altered during GSEA), they can do so by:

networkMORE(regpcond_filtered, group1 = '1', cytoscape = FALSE, pathway = 'Glycolysis pathway')
